<br>
That reminded me of a kid who had a similar cancer. A lady came into my airbrush shop looking for airbrush supplies. She was buying it for the boy who only had a few days to live. His dream was to airbrush...and I took it for granted because I had done it for so many years.<br>
<br>
I offered to teach the boy and she was very happy to hear that. The shop owner also donated supplies for him. <br>
<br>
When I arrived at the boy's house, I saw a young lad around 10 or 11. He did not look unhealthy nor looked like death was coming.  I introduced myself and we went inside. I happily tutored him the basics of the airbrush. He was happy as was his father and lady who went searching for airbrush supplies.<br>
<br>
A few days later the boy died. His last expressions were airbrushed on the bedroom wall, childish looking art of things that boy loved...I dont remember what I did...if I cried or just left work for a day.  Death of someone you didn't really know but had an affect on their life is something I was not prepared for.(This was in 1992). <br>
<br>
But this taught me, I did take life for granted when I thought I did not. 10 years have passed and I had not thought of that boy till you mentioned your friend. <p><BR><img src=http://cableone.net/dragonwhelp/muse/signature/banjamad.gif>
